<DOC><DOCNO> AP881118-0200 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-18-88 0916EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-AnchorBank     11-18 0235</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Anchor Bank,0245</SECOND><HEAD>Anchor Savings Bank, Cruise Line Operators Reach Understanding</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Anchor Savings Bank has agreed to be acquired for$170 million in cash by the Hamilton Holding Co., whose principalowner controls Ensign Bank and Carnival Cruise Lines Inc.   The two institutions would have combined assets of $10.3 billionand branches throughout the Atlantic seaboard, making it one of thenation's five largest savings institutions.   Under the agreement announced late Thursday, Hamilton would pay$9.75 a share in cash for all of Anchor's outstanding common shares.In addition, Hamilton was granted an option to acquire about amillion shares of a new issue of common stock, also at $9.75 ashare, according to a news release.   The offer requires approval from regulators and stockholders.   Anchor, which is among the nation's 25 largest savingsinstitutions, operates branches throughout the New York region,Georgia and Florida, and has two mortgage banking subsidiaries.   Hamilton, an Atlanta holding company, is controlled by TedArison, the principal owner of Carnival. Hamilton also owns all ofEnsign Financial Corp., which operates Ensign Bank. Ensign Bank hasbranches in metropolitan New York and in Florida.   Last month, Carnival lost in its attempt to take over RoyalAdmiral Cruises Ltd. when Anders Wilhelmsen andamp; Co., a Norwegianpartner in Royal Admiral, exercised its right to buy the 70 percentof Carnival stock it did not already own.</TEXT></DOC>